issue.body:
We have proof with this structure:

```rust
assert(post) by {
    match(step) {
        A(..) => {
            // ...
            assert(post);
        },
        B(..) => {
            // ...
            assert(post);
        },
        _ => {}
    }
}
```

If I mask A with `assume(false)`, `assert(post)` in B passes; if I remove the `assume(false)` in branch A, `assert(post)` in B breaks (or takes long time which suggests more flakiness). The actual code can be found [here](https://github.com/anvil-verifier/anvil/pull/716/commits/3d49319326dfcdcc34b6b8663f0445a7fa97293e) where the assertion is broken.

I opened a thread discussing this on Zulip, and @Chris-Hawblitzel suggested it may be achieved with an attribute on `match`. So I open an issue here to give some actual examples where the feature is super helpful. Without it, we have to split the proof into multiple sub-proofs for different branches, and have to
- repeat preconditions
- manually add assumptions proved just before each branch explicitly

`if-else` has the same [problem](https://github.com/anvil-verifier/anvil/pull/716/commits/a6b681a855a6408e67e265928f1c1326f236e42b).

Thank you!

